\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each following item matches a different step in the interface’s conception.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first defined the website’s use.
 The following rules allow us to set up definite interfaces and processes.
 With these transparent rules, we wanted to avoid the user to feel lost.
 Simplicity is the main idea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The item
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A swap can only be done with goods.
 Services can not be swapped (for now).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The swap
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The swap is on a one to one basis.
 It is therefore only possible to swap a good for another good.
 Barter cancels an item’s financial value ; checking that the swap is fair
 is the users’ responsibility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Communication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The swap process concerns the item.
 The communication between the supplier and the seeker is reduced to the
 item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Users’ profiles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a barter website, there are two main uses, therefore two types of user:
 the one who supplies something to swap, and the one who is looking for
 something to swap.
 Here are non-exhaustive lists of possible motivations, for the two different
 profiles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The supplier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supplier can have different reasons to put an item at disposal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No or no more use of the item (ex: toddler’s clothes)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No or no more space (ex: moving away, cumbersome gift)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No or no more time (ex: video game, exercise bicycle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Old-fashioned (ex: furniture, decorations) Used (ex: book, video game)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recycling (ex: will to give an old TV a second life)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Savings (ex: to put a rare item at disposal in order to swap it for another
 useful item)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sentimentality (ex: not wanting an item to be destroyed)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The seeker
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identified here a list of possible reasons for someone to look for an
 item:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Free (complementary to “no more use”)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Newness (ex: liking to change the content of a wardrobe often
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Seeking a good deal or an added value (ex: professionals)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Impulsivity (ex: to consume)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To complete a collection (ex: stamps, dishes, spoons)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To find an item unavailable anywhere else (ex: 1602 waffle iron)
\end_layout

